# 2. Build a frequency table for Grade by Gender, 
# and a side-by-side bar graph for grade by gender
# (remember to use label and legend).

fts = ftable(df$Grade, df$Gender)

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
barplot(fts, beside=TRUE, col=coolColors, names = c("Female","Male")
        , main="Grade by Gender")
abline(h = c(1,2,3,4,5,6),  lty = 2, col = "grey")
abline(v = c(6.5),  lty = 2, col = "grey")

legend("topright", c("A","B","C", "D", "F"), fill=coolColors)

# The males had 1/3 as many 'A's as the females.
# There was one failed male and one female.

# 3. Do a chi-square test of independence between Gender and Grade.

chi = chisq.test(m)
chi
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  m
## X-squared = 2.8475, df = 4, p-value = 0.5837

# The chi square test issued a warning because many of the expected values

# 8. Do a single scatterplot to predict Height based on Age using color
# for gender and histograms on the side. 

library(UsingR)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
gen = matrix(df[,1])
gen = unclass(gen)
gen = replace(gen, gen=="m", "lightblue")
gen = replace(gen, gen=="f", "lightpink")
h = matrix(df[,3])
a = matrix(df[,4])
# Original Data
simple.scatterplot(a,h,col=gen, pch=19)

## Removed 3 tall outliers. ##
no_out = subset(df, df[,3] < 140)
gen_n = matrix(no_out[,1])
gen_n = unclass(gen)
gen_n = replace(gen, gen=="m", "lightblue")
gen_n = replace(gen, gen=="f", "lightpink")
h_n = matrix(no_out[,3])
a_n = matrix(no_out[,4])
# Data with no outliers
simple.scatterplot(a_n,h_n,col=gen_n, pch=19)

# Removing the outliers provides for a more accurate regression

# 13. Find the residuals for the model in (10) and describe their distribution
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
# Original Data
model1 <- lm(h ~ a, data = df)
model1
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = h ~ a, data = df)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)            a  
##     167.218       -4.659
barplot(abs(model1$residuals), col="green", main="Abs of residuals with outliers")
plot(model1$residuals, pch=19, main="Residuals Original Data",col="#23b832", xlab="Predicted",ylab="Residuals")
abline(h = c(0),  lty = 2, col = "grey")

#Abs = absolute value.

# No Outliers
model2 <- lm(h_n ~ a_n, data = no_out)
model2
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = h_n ~ a_n, data = no_out)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)          a_n  
##      38.694        1.545
barplot(abs(model2$residuals), col="green", main="Abs of residuals with no outliers")
plot(model2$residuals, pch=19, main="Residuals no outliers", col="#23b832", xlab="Predicted",ylab="Residuals")
abline(h = c(0),  lty = 2, col = "grey")

## In both the cases of data with and without outliers 
## the residuals are rarely perfectly plotted on the regression line.
## this indicates that the regression may not be an excellent predictor
## of height based on the individuals age.

# 14. Test the normality of the residuals -using Shapiro Test of normality

#Test with outliers
shapiro.test(model1$residuals)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  model1$residuals
## W = 0.6698, p-value = 4.29e-07
#Test with no outliers
shapiro.test(model2$residuals)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  model2$residuals
## W = 0.96114, p-value = 0.3709
# The data is normal if the p-value is above 0.05. 
# So we now know our variable is not normally distributed.
